Title: Create a dialog on music for twenty sentences
Description: Create a dialog on music for twenty sentences
Keywords: dialog, chat, music, entertainment, arts, conversation, writing
Answer.sentence1: Is there anything you miss about the pre-Internet, pre-MP3 era of music.
Answer.sentence10: Exactly my point. It's all kind of disposable if you don't like it right away.
Answer.sentence11: I miss growing with an album and an album growing with me.
Answer.sentence12: That experience certainly is still possible, I recently did it with Pinegrove's latest album, but it's a conscious decision to do so rather than being built in.
Answer.sentence13: I also miss the social experience of the music store. Bumping into people, striking up conversations, talking to the staff, et cetera.
Answer.sentence14: You can do all of that online now though!
Answer.sentence15: Yeah, but it's not the same as human connection. We have Facebook, but it hasn't supplanted our need to see each other in person.
Answer.sentence16: Point taken. Did you ever get any great recommendations in store?
Answer.sentence17: Yes, a clerk once referred me to check out The Modern Lovers. That was an epic day in the development of my music taste.
Answer.sentence18: I had a similar experience with someone recommending David Bowie at the record store after seeing that I picked out Modest Mouse. His passion was contagious.
Answer.sentence19: Yeah, that's lost these days. You only really see it at shows.
Answer.sentence2: Oh sure, there's tons! I think we devalue music now.
Answer.sentence20: I know, I'm feeling nostalgic for CDs right now, but I also don't wanna give up my access to the majority of everything ever recorded being at my fingertips.
Answer.sentence3: Are you making an economic argument. That when there is an unlimited supply you might value each product less.
Answer.sentence4: Sort of, but it's more nuanced than that.
Answer.sentence5: Well what is it?
Answer.sentence6: I think that back in the day, when the costs to getting an album were higher, it was a different experience.
Answer.sentence7: Yeah, sure, but how is that relevant.
Answer.sentence8: Well, you were making a commitment when you bought an album. You'd go to a store, look around for a while, buy one cd, say Radiohead OK Computer for 19 dollars, drive, bike, or walk back home and sit with that record.
Answer.sentence9: Ah, I see what you're saying. We don't have to sit with stuff anymore.
